text: today i walked in the womens march and i'm so in awe of the bravery of the speakers, my fellow protestors, and this amazing team i walked with. we must speak up; we will not go back. up until now, i've been hesitant to be too explicit about my identity and beliefs online. i was told to be afraid of what a potential employer might think when they see my social media. but i will no longer hide and be afraid. i am proud to be a feminist, bisexual, depressed survivor. if a potential employer (or anyone) doesn't support me because of that, i don't want to work with you anyway. #wewillnotgoback #womenswave #metoo

text:
i know that you won‚Äôt remember the march, but i hope that you will remember a few other things. i hope you will remember that the privilege of your life comes with the responsibility to speak up. i hope that you will not wait to see your gender, your nationality, your religion, or your sexual orientation targeted before you take action. i hope that you will recognize humanity in all of its forms and always see yourself in the struggles of others. i hope that you will be slow to accept barriers and quick take up burdens and carry banners. i hope you will spend your whole life marching.
i want to raise a fully informed child who will speak his mind when marginalized people are being targeted by the bully leading the government all the way down to the bully on the playground at school. üíï

text:
i‚Äôve sat in the discomfort this year of seeing how whiteness and feminism intersect and often oppress. following women of color, reading books on white fragility and intersectionality and leaning into new spaces have been important. and, i continue to hold space for non-binary thinking that two or more opposing truths can be true at the same time, which is why my girlfriends and i booked a flight and joined the women‚Äôs march in dc. non-dualistic thinking allows me to recognize that both palestinian and jewish lives matter. that both pro-life and pro-choice conversations are important. non-dualistic think allows me to be curious about people‚Äôs stories and choices that are different than mine. as i marched today i thought of the dozens of women who sat in my office this year sharing their own survival stories of rape, sexual harassment, domestic violence and torture and i yelled louder in response. racism, sexism, misogyny, ableism, homophobia, transphobia, islamaphobia and anti-semticism are embedded in american institutions‚Äîhad enough of it?! yeah, #metoo. üëäüèªüëäüèªüëäüèª

text:

33 are reported to police
29 are recorded as a crime
12 have charges laid
6 are prosecuted
3 lead to conviction
and 997 assailants walk free?

text: feeling revived, empowered, inspired, and assured to march with ~7,000 progressive voices in arizona today. this year, the march was riddled with unfortunate though much-needed fractioning and difficult yet crucial discussions, and i was a little hesitant to attend. however, i was thrilled to see native women, trans women, women of color, immigrants, muslim women, and alter-abled women centered as speakers and organizers of today's phoenix march. many spoke of the necessity of intersectionality within the women's march movement, within feminism, & within #metoo, and many speakers reminded us that women of color have been fighting these same fights for decades before us. a truly unforgettable day. thank you, phoenix - keep it up!! #knowyourherstory #noticewhoisntatthetable #womensmarch #phoenixwomensmarch

text:
3/26 weeks of feminism is here!! ‚Äúfeminism seeks not to erase what is, but to add to it, lifting up the voices of those who do not fall within the narrow confines of the few categories offered by a heteropatriarchicalcaptitalist society. through feminism we can expand our vocabulary and broaden existing definitions so that more people are empowered to speak and understand their experiences. this understanding is essential for identifying what is problematic and taking action to achieve change and liberation for all. without a feminist vocabulary, oppressed peoples are defined in terms of negations: by what they lack in relation to the heterociswhite male. everyone (read: men, womxn, nonbinary folk, trans people, poc, etc.) deserves the chance to articulate who they are and what it is like to be them. the scope of our language determines the scope of our beliefs, actions, and interpretations. language gives rise to ideology, which lies at the basis of society and is the groundwork for political institutions which perpetuate existing power structures. without feminism, we are steeped in a language which privileges some and oppresses many. 
feminism acknowledges that many oppressed peoples are burdened by the daunting task of reconciling multiple experiences of self, many of which conflict and cause immense cognitive dissonance. feminism gave me anger. it said, ‚Äúhere, take this, use it. sadness is not the only female emotion.‚Äù i felt angry at my rapists, instead of feeling shameful, helpless and depressed. feminism granted me permission to say: ‚Äúit‚Äôs not my fault‚Äù and ‚Äúi didn‚Äôt deserve that, no matter what anyone tells me (implicitly or explicitly).‚Äù in a feminist world, i would be able to out my rapist and know that people would come to my defense if he sought revenge. i would have the peace of mind knowing that people know who he is and can protect themselves from experiencing what he did to me and many other women. feminism is the realization of everyone‚Äôs right to their own reality. through feminism, we create new discourses in which people tell their own stories and write their own narratives.‚Äù

text:
this month, three years ago i felt like i lost my innocence. i got this tattoo of a daisy not only to represent my favorite flower but to take back the innocence i felt like i lost. here is to the strength i have gained and the love i have recieved. üåº

over the years, i have seen many people from my church, childhood friends and my parents friends post things like ‚Äúit was her fault‚Äù, ‚Äúwhy was she wearing that?‚Äù i just urge everyone  to rethink what you post because you never know who‚Äôs seeing it and listening. what you say right now tells other people in your life whether they can disclose their own experiences to you and ask for help. #metoo

text:
all 5‚Äô 2‚Äù of me proudly carried this sign through the women‚Äôs march on washington this year (with frequent arm breaks üòâ). although, no sign could possibly ever encompass every issue i am passionate about - it captures the bulk. 
i‚Äôm still angry about the 800,000 government workers who are not being paid. i‚Äôm still angry about how nc district - 09, my house district and maybe yours in charlotte or other areas in nc is the only unrepresented house district in the entire united states due to an investigation of criminal conduct and absentee voter fraud against the mark harris campaign. 
i understand a lot of you think marches are dumb or useless and that‚Äôs totally fine. one quote i‚Äôve always posted in my room throughout my life is this: ‚Äúour lives begin to end the day we stay silent about things that matter.‚Äù - mlk jr. 
on the days i ask myself why i even bother trying to get through to people, i think about that quote. it may not make a difference in changing minds but i hope all of you who have faced discrimination  because you‚Äôre gay, or have felt unwanted because you are an immigrant, or felt mistreated just because of the color of your skin understand that you have allies in this life - and we won‚Äôt stop fighting for you and telling people when they‚Äôre wrong. 
for further lighter inspiration, here‚Äôs my new favorite quote featured on a sign today, in reference to the government shutdown: ‚Äúthis shit is really fucking serious, bro.‚Äù -cardi b ‚ù§Ô∏è #womenswave2019 #womensmarchdc #freedomplaza

text: #womensmarch2019¬† you can now pre-order, "the me too movement of the bible," now @¬†https://www.amazon.com/dp/b07mtlv47w‚Ä¶¬†on instagram click the link in the bio!¬†#metoo¬†#timesup¬†#muterkelly¬†#godsaystimesup¬†my next book, "the me too movement of the bible." understanding the will of god through the word of god and the me too movement i had great hesitation in writing a book about the me too movement and the bible. in my hesitation, i begin to think that maybe a woman should write this book. in this book, i would be challenged to write about things that most preachers never preach or teach in their bible lessons. the sunday school lessons that are written never deal with the issue of sexual assault. most books that are written in the christian arena never deal with the issues that will be discussed in this book. i am about to write about something that if i came across in a movie, i would turn the movie off because i do not find such matters entertaining even in the world of make-believe movies.  but in dealing with these kinds of issues in real life you can't turn it off. you can't fast forward through the scenes that you don't like in real life. many who will read this book wish they could turn it off or fast forward through the pain. this book is a book written for all the silent victims of sexual harassment and sexual assault. i pray that god will use this book to heal all the hurt and the shame that surrounds these heinous crimes. coming spring 2019 ...take a look at dr. eaton's other books at¬†amazon.com/author/revdrmichaeleaton

text: üá™üá∏ por favor, evitemos que el dolor de una ruptura nos lleve a generalizaciones. no soy terapista ni psic√≥logo, s√≥lo soy una sobreviviente de relaciones narcisistas familiares y de parejas, y hoy me parece muy importante pedir que seamos muy honestos con nosotros mismos, que busquemos ayuda de especialistas y estudiemos las diferentes caracter√≠sticas de los narcisistas antes de acusar a nuestras exparejas y exponerlos p√∫blicamente, porque de alg√∫n modo, eso tambi√©n es violencia y abuso. somos humanos, tenemos diferentes ca≈ïacteres, no hay relaciones perfectas y todos tenemos d√≠as no tan buenos que pueden llevar a desacuerdos y discusiones, sin que eso signifique que estemos relacionados con narcisistas. aprovechemos toda la informaci√≥n que recibimos a diario de las diferentes cuentas para aprender, entender y sanar, y no para lastimar o vengarnos de aquel nos lastim√≥. por favor, no generalicemos!. ‚ù§ ‚úí: yo. üá∫üá∏ please, let us avoid that the pain of a rupture leads us to generalizations. i am not a therapist or a psychologist, i am just a survivor of family and couple narcissistic relationships, and today it seems very important to ask that we be very honest with ourselves, that we seek help from specialists and study the different characteristics of narcissists before accusing our ex-partners and expose them publicly, because in a way, that is also violence and abuse. we are human, we have different characters, there are no perfect relationships and we all have not so good days that can lead to disagreements and discussions, without this meaning that we are related to narcissists. take advantage of all the information that we receive on a daily basis from the different accounts to learn, understand and heal, and not to hurt or take revenge on that one that hurt us. please, do not generalize! text:
thank-you so much for the unbelievable support we have received the last few days.

we are sorry the insecurities of a few people were vocal, but your counterpoints were amazing.

we‚Äôre sorry their toxic behaviors keep them from knowing how amazing we all are.
truth be told, we are their brothers and sisters, cops and soldiers, bartenders and clergy. we live next to them, hell we may even live with them.
we aren‚Äôt trying to ruin their lives, but the days of living as a lesser version of anyone are done.
we‚Äôve stood together in the resistance, we supported one another in the #metoo movement, and we‚Äôll continue our stance as we honor the history of stonewall50.

keep your spirits strong folks, we‚Äôre in the fight together.

text:
solidarity. 
i‚Äôm so bummed to not be out on the streets with all today. and i know i‚Äôm like a broken record here but i find it so important‚Äîstanding up for what you believe in‚Äîso, to those marching today who fight for the rights of others as hard as they do their own, thank you!! you are strong. and i am with you in spirit.
.
i stand with those women & allies who march knowing:
#blacklivesmatter
those who fight to #endracism 
to stop #policebrutality 
to dismantle a system built on profiting from #massincarceration
to #stopxenophobia 
to #createequality 
to establish equity
 and for all of those who know all too well‚Äîfirsthand‚Äî#metoo
for women‚Äôs rights & choice & planned parenthood & sex education 
to #shutdownmisogyny
and #endthegovernmentshutdown 
i stand with those who work to #endsexism and #homophobia who #buildsafespaces and #protecttranslives
.
to all those who know #nohumanisillegal and that #migrationisnotacrime. what is going on at our borders, the separation of families, the inhumane treatment and the criminalization of immigrants is not to be tolerated. the act of separation itself is criminal‚Äîand racist.
.
we cannot settle into complacency or apathy. we cannot let what has become ‚Äònormal‚Äô in our society necessarily become equated with what is right. we need to first imagine and then work towards better‚Äîfor all.
.
i am with you if you #buildbridgesnotwalls 
you of the bigger table theory. 
we must fight through #intersectionality and from a place of #lovenothate .

as we progress and move towards betterment‚Äîwe must #thinkgloballyactlocally and #fightforothersrights as we do our own. there is no real ‚Äòother‚Äô ‚Äî that is a construct, a sham.
.
we are all connected
.

there is so much work to be done. and we have to start with ourselves. make a practice of checking ourselves. listening more. and doing the work, speaking up in our own circles‚Äîfamilies, friends, workplaces, neighborhoods, communities. having the hard conversations with our own men, boys, girls. in our everyday. it‚Äôs to us. every one of us.
.
#womensmarch2019
#womensmarchoakland
#womensmarchposter
.

power to the people. keep on.
.

text:
animals need our help üòî rp @macielleslie @theresialovesallanimals @animaltruthandhope @theresialovesallanimals
@animaltruthandhope @meat_your_future. please watch until the end. like bulls used in bullfighting, this baby calf has a spear in his back, weakening his muscle strength and likely interfering with his range of motion/ability to move. notice how he frequently falls and sits.
.
he is stabbed, again and again, as the young bullfighter "practices."
.
can you imagine being a child and being attacked/stabbed like this, over and over until you finally die? not even our worst nightmares come close to the horrifying reality these confused, sweet animals face.
.
what a shameful sight. what an embarrassment to our species that we even ‚Äúenjoy‚Äù these spectacles under the guise of "culture."
.
your reaction may be that of disgust, and rightfully so.  but, have you considered where your milk, leather, meat, and other animal products come from?
.
please know that, if you are still consuming those animal products, you are paying for something equally terrible to be imposed upon animals.
.
the animals we commoditize for things like meat, milk, leather, wool and fur, similarly suffer horror and pain, even though we may not witness it as clearly as the spectacle in this video. there is simply no way to turn a living, breathing animal into food or other products without immense suffering and violence.
.
actually, dairy in particular results in the killing of millions of baby male calves (some dairy calves, we imagine, may even be used for "practice stabbing" like in the video). this is because, in order to produce milk, cows must be continuously impregnated, and male calves are useless to the dairy industry and thus are discarded.
.

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

text:
üíô‚úäüíö‚úäüèªüíõ‚úäüèºüß°‚úäüèΩüíú‚úäüèæüñ§‚úäüèø today, along with so many other women and men all over the united states, i participated in the 3rd annual woman's march. 
as this being my first march, i was a little unsure what to expect. though the daytona march was small, it was a group filled with men and women of all ages wanting the same thing. 
equallity for all. healthcare for all. human rights for all.

love vs hate. 
towards the end of the march,  as my girlfriends and i were walking back, something happened. which was pretty much a slap in the face. 
on my drive home, i really took some time to reflect on exactly what happened. and contemplated whether or not i was going to share this experience. 
well, i decided that i will not be silent - because i matter, we matter, all humans matter. and we as a society need to stop these 'norms' from happening.

i will not censor my following statement, so please stop here if you are easily offended. i will not be quiet on this to make people comfortable. especially when the following vulgar statement was made with intent - to be uncomfortable. he knew he could catcall and get away with it.

this 20 something man was taught that this behavior was ok. and it is not! it is not ok, to drive past women and yell out of your window, "i would 'fuck' every one of you". this isnt the first time statements like this have been made to myself or others. but acts like these, need to stop. 
things like this are the exact reason, why marchs like these are happening. 
nevertheless, she persisted. 
#resist #wearethechange #whywemarch #wematter #metoo #myvoice #mybody #rise
#usingmyright #checkyourself #wecandobetter #womenswave #stopcatcalls #outthem

text:
‚Äúyou are here to thrive you are here to lead you are here to do things that others don't have the courage to do and you are here to do them well.‚Äù
.
i really couldn't decide what image i wanted to use to honor everyone out there marching today. in 2017, what struck me about the #womensmarch in los angeles was the sheer volume of people and the peace i felt walking with such a large crowd. in 2018, marching with my infant child in tow was so fulfilling, and i witnessed many many women doing the same, marching alongside their children.
.
this year, in 2019, while i am not in the streets riding the #womenswave, i am marching in spirit, trying to create change through action, in this project, helping foster a community where we build each other up, offer support to women and mothers who need more day to day than we like to admit and a safe place to both celebrate and mourn. this picture sums up #whyimarch
.
the seeds of change take time to show any real progress, but i'm sure there are notable differences present between the march in 2019 compared to 2017. those in attendance around the world, what do you see?

text:
rough times 
can a seemingly peaceful landscape be full of trouble? i imagine the tempest by turner and all the characters that could be in it. 
today was #womensmarch and i was reflecting on how the #metoo movement has affected the world. i was also reflecting on the fact that there are demonstrations over the macedonian issue and how a city can go from being relatively quiet to being loud and taken over by people. 
alas is change coming?

.
.
.

text:
women‚Äôs march in dc, 2017
.
seven of us drove in a van to the 2017 women‚Äôs march in dc. it was an utterly surreal, empowering, life changing weekend. it was the first time i‚Äòd felt not alone in years. 
a few hours outside of dc, there was this two hour standstill at this toll ‚Äî and every other car ‚Äî in the sea of *thousands* of cars all around us ‚Äî were women with women‚Äôs march posters, pink hats, whatever. everyone was cheering each other on and it was chilling and i cried. i had not felt so much support in years and years. i finally wasn‚Äôt alone. there are people out there that care ‚Äî they care about *me*, they care about *women*, they care about all the humans in this country and people on this planet, and the hundreds of millions of them are willing to fight ‚Äî for me, for you, for our future and the world. it was the first time i‚Äôd actually felt hope for my future in so many, many year. thank you so much for your love. we got this.
.
i love you @carmenmyersreed @yourpaldavidvevo @sklont @ericawhoo and kelsey and joyce üíó
.

text:
as a board member of @tacomaopera, one of my jobs is to share information about our upcoming performances that feature world-class talent in intimate theaters with very affordable ticket prices...how‚Äôd i do with my sales pitch? üòÄ

i am excited to share a video i found in association with tacoma opera‚Äôs next performance, benjamin britten‚Äôs 1946 opera, ‚Äúthe rape of lucretia‚Äù.
.
.
 https://youtu.be/bbevv8jpecek

first‚Ä¶yes‚Ä¶the title. although it is often described as one of the most beautiful modern chamber operas, ‚Äúlucretia‚Äù is indeed a story from ancient rome (circa 590bc) in which a happily married noblewoman, lucretia, is raped by tarquinius, the son of an etruscan king. the crime and injustice is said to have prompted a rebellion that led to the overthrow of rome‚Äôs monarchy and ultimately to rome‚Äôs transition from a kingdom to a republic.
.
.
second‚Ä¶i am incredibly proud of the artistic team of tacoma opera who very boldly and intentionally chose to perform this opera in support of the #metoo movement. .
.
the video is from a 2015 performance of "lucretia" in england directed by fiona shaw (yes, that fiona shaw, who many know from the harry potter film series). shaw describes "lucretia" as: ‚Äúa short story about a terrible night, but its really about the love between a husband and a wife, what it is to be in a marriage, and to have that marriage ripped apart.‚Äù .
.
.
even if you are not able to attend one of tacoma opera‚Äôs performances, i encourage you to watch the video to learn more about this beautiful modern opera that is incredibly timely given the challenges our society is facing today. 
#tacomaopera #opera #chamberopera #therapeoflucretia #fionashaw #benjaminbritten #tacoma #tacomaarts

at the last march‚Äôs women‚Äôs empowerment principles forum held by the united nations (where awlo was represented), the cruciality of women‚Äôs empowerment was the focus to attain year 2030 sustainable development goals.

.
african women in leadership conference holds this year at rwanda on 4th and 5th april 2019 at kigali marriott hotel.
.
african women in leadership conference is a meeting for strategies and capacity building to advance women's leadership. it engages key decision makers to generate solutions, implement best practices, and build partnerships  for women's development.
awlc mainly engages its first stakeholders - the women, to increase leadership participation. since effective strategies originate from women, through equipment for leadership positioning.

essay: #metoo
{tw: abuse, domestic violence}
the #metoo movement was one of the hot topics i was infuriating with. 
my mother was assaulted by my father...‚Äùhe was such a nice‚Äù guy. her family members didn‚Äôt do anything out of fear for her and their own safety.
i was physically, emotionally, and verbally abused by my father up until i was 15. i came to school with bruises on my arms; my friends noticed and asked me who hurt me. when i told them it was my father, the first thing they said is that i needed to tell someone. we went to our school counselor, who immediately called the police, came to my school, and took photos of my bruises. 
my father denied beating me, and when i got home, i was threatened some more. he told me i was a liar, and he never hit me, (as he was hitting me). one time i blacked out, and he screamed at me until i woke up. he threatened me with lies that the givers would put my three younger brothers in foster homes and i would never see them again.
i hate that men (and women) control people with fear and hatred, i despise that we live in a society where men say ‚Äúfacts‚Äù and women speak their truth it‚Äôs say ‚Äúfiction,‚Äù or we‚Äôre ‚Äúcrazy‚Äù or ‚Äúdesperate for attention.‚Äù
i tell my story so others won‚Äôt feel alone. you don‚Äôt have to feel alone, and like my middle school friends, we can get through this together.
my father was never arrested for these acts, and people were afraid to press charges. child protective services weren‚Äôt supportive of my case because why didn‚Äôt call before if this was occurring my whole life?
the answer: my father would probably have hospitalized me by then.
today i won‚Äôt be at the march. instead, i plan on donating money to weave sacramento so they continue to help women with children leave their abusive partners.
‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ
may you feel empowered this weekend by whatever moves you.
and don‚Äôt forget, you‚Äôre not alone.
1-800-799-7233‚Äìnational domestic violence hotline.

text:
thank you, to all those out in the streets today standing against the oppression that exists in the world. i want to join you but i‚Äôm exhausted so here‚Äôs a sign of my support from home. i didn‚Äôt get a lot of sleep last night. after witnessing the backlash to the recent gillette ad asking men to be the best they can be, i engaged in a discussion around why some men are so upset.
.
according to jordan peterson, an influential psychologist, i‚Äôm just too sensitive, too agreeable and too passive and therefore deserve to be relegated to the inferior ranks of women and minorities. he (jordan‚Äôs preferred pronoun - please search his name and bill c-16 for further detail) believes, as do many of his followers, that men hold the most power because they are the most competent. it‚Äôs just natural selection. it‚Äôs evolution. masculine traits of aggressiveness and competitiveness are superior to feminine traits like agreeableness and compassion and these masculine traits are associated to power and leadership.
.
apparently, gillette asking men to encourage their sons to be empathetic, their daughters to be strong, and to model behaviour that shows respect for women and discourages violence against anyone is crossing a line. it seems that men don‚Äôt want to be lectured, at least not by a company that they are used to promoting a less progressive kind of masculinity.
.
according to at least one jordan peterson follower, it‚Äôs important to listen to his entire lecture and not just clips because those can be taken out of context. hence my lack of sleep.  you‚Äôll need to get through over two hours of his talk called identity politics and the marxist lie of white privilege before you get to his dismissive take on intersectionality and his opinion that white privilege is really just majority privilege and, really, what‚Äôs the problem with that?
.
it‚Äôs interesting to observe that, in a culture so dominated by capitalist patriarchal thinking, an ad for razors could offer such a telling perspective on the state of equality.
.
now, off to the forest with me.
.
#feminist #whitefeminism #privilege #equality #dobetter #resistance #resilience #metoo #womensmarch #womenwhohike #hikebc

text:
new podcast with @tobinzivon! ep56: tobin zivon on authentic relating in the age of #metoo, open relating, polyamory and meeting a partner.
.
this podcast was per special request from those of you who wanted guidance or further talk about open relationships, polyamory and monogamy. tobin is my go-to for this as he has experimented and deeply lived with them at all.
.
what he shares:
.
some of the golden rules of healthy relating
the important ingredients to a flourishing relationship
how to reduce drama in your relationship, regardless of structure
his shift from ‚Äòdoing‚Äô to ‚Äòbeing‚Äô
.

what you‚Äôll hear:
.
moving into authenticity and vulnerability to allow a genuine unfolding within a relationship
discerning when to be vulnerable and when to respect your communication boundaries
finding the living sweet spot of authenticity, vulnerability, and being transparent within each relationship
having ruthless self-awareness toward yourself and your conditioning
following the truth of your heart in your relationship structure
discovering alignment, or not, with your partner
ways to proceed with changes in your relationship dynamic
celebrating your partner in their fullness
healing your attachment styles, wounding, and imprints to have less drama in a relationship
expanding beyond the paradigm of dichotomy
showing up from a deeper conscious commitment to self, to source, and to each other
finding full comfort in who you are and what you want
living the fully embodied wholeness that you‚Äôre here to live
loosening your scripts while maintaining togetherness
finding a way to embody and transmit an experience of safety for you partner
being based in love and integrity, not in impulses of conditioning
recognizing the energetic shift post metoo, and embracing the role of initiator as a woman
meeting your partner at their emotional and communication belt levels
#magamamapodcast #healthyrelating #relationshipcatalyst

text:
the questions
the thoughts
anxiety
the feeling of shame and dirt 
yet you see this but you don‚Äôt stop the questions 
you dig deeper into the wound and you try to find the root of the problem
but putting everything to the back of my mind until i‚Äôm ready to talk about it or even report it 
is how i cope, 
i appreciate you for your worry but i‚Äôve dealt with this all alone in the past and i will continue to do this
because i‚Äôm all that i have 
no one else will help me or understand me except me
i hope you understand 
don‚Äôt look at me as a victim
i can tell the way your eyes water up when you ask me a question or listen to my answer
you see me and think ‚Äúpoor thing‚Äù
i don‚Äôt want to be a victim
i don‚Äôt even want to be anything -denise‚õà

flashback friday to the women‚Äôs march sacramento 2018.

essay: #metoo
{tw: abuse, domestic violence}
the #metoo movement was one of the hot topics i was infuriating with. 
my mother was assaulted by my father...‚Äùhe was such a nice‚Äù guy. her family members didn‚Äôt do anything out of fear for her and their own safety.
i was physically, emotionally, and verbally abused by my father up until i was 15. i came to school with bruises on my arms; my friends noticed and asked me who hurt me. when i told them it was my father, the first thing they said is that i needed to tell someone. we went to our school counselor, who immediately called the police, came to my school, and took photos of my bruises. 
my father denied beating me, and when i got home, i was threatened some more. he told me i was a liar, and he never hit me, (as he was hitting me). one time i blacked out, and he screamed at me until i woke up. he threatened me with lies that the givers would put my three younger brothers in foster homes and i would never see them again.
i hate that men (and women) control people with fear and hatred, i despise that we live in a society where men say ‚Äúfacts‚Äù and women speak their truth it‚Äôs say ‚Äúfiction,‚Äù or we‚Äôre ‚Äúcrazy‚Äù or ‚Äúdesperate for attention.‚Äù
i tell my story so others won‚Äôt feel alone. you don‚Äôt have to feel alone, and like my middle school friends, we can get through this together.
my father was never arrested for these acts, and people were afraid to press charges. child protective services weren‚Äôt supportive of my case because why didn‚Äôt call before if this was occurring my whole life?
the answer: my father would probably have hospitalized me by then.
today i won‚Äôt be at the march. instead, i plan on donating money to weave sacramento so they continue to help women with children leave their abusive partners.
‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ
may you feel empowered this weekend by whatever moves you.
and don‚Äôt forget, you‚Äôre not alone.
1-800-799-7233‚Äìnational domestic violence hotline.

text: although there was a low turnout this year, matt and i still felt we must march. every year i march for a different purpose. last year, it was to shine light on how much women are underrepresented in congress. this year, i march for all women and girls who have been victims of sexual violence and harassment. i march for black girls everywhere who‚Äôs voices are not being heard and stories are not being told. i march for survivors who were not believed when they tried to report their assault and for survivors who have yet to tell their stories out of fear of being called a liar. i believe dr. christine blasey ford. i still believe anita hill. i believe women and together, we will be the change. time is up on the old saying boys will be boys. men must be held accountable for their actions. i have so many good men in my life so i know men can do better. i believe in you just like how i believe in the so many amazing women who have come forward these past few years even if it means risking everything. we must do better. we can do better. #metoo #timesup

this is a problem, even if you don‚Äôt see these issues in your daily life, it‚Äôs still there. 
sexual assault is a fucking felony but so many people treat it like it‚Äôs not a problem. 1 in 6 women, 1 in 7 children, and 1 in 33 men are raped. that‚Äôs not including other forms of sexual assault. 1 in 3 women will be sexually abused or assaulted while in college. that is not okay! for those who think that sexual assault is just a joke, unfollow me now. i was four when i was fingered at church. i wasn‚Äôt much older when my step grandpa attempted to do the same thing. i‚Äôve been cat called and made uncomfortable and it‚Äôs not okay.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text: to dr. christine blasey-ford, who endured one of the most profound acts of bravery that i‚Äôve ever witnessed: thank you. thank you for sharing your truth despite a shaking voice and the knowledge that in a nation that elected a sexual predator as potus, the outcome would likely be unchanged. thank you for risking *everything* to speak a truth you owed no one and for doing so in the most public and painful way i can imagine, while displaying fierce integrity and grace throughout. your unforgettable courage matters despite the outcome. in this #metoo era, we‚Äôve seen time and again the domino effect that results when survivors break their silence. thank you for using your voice to speak on behalf of not only yourself, but an entire world of women whose stories of sexual violence echo yours in one way or another. thank you for trusting us to carry your pain with you and for making us all a little braver.

text:
the women's march has been roiled in controversy since its inception, from initial concerns about a lack of diverse leadership to anti-semitism. still, hundreds of thousands are marching across north america and in sister marches around the world today because of a belief in a cause (or causes) that transcend the boundaries of the women's march as an organization.‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
started as a response to the election of donald trump and held the day after his inauguration, the 2017 women's march was the largest protest in the country's history, drawing 1% of the country's population to the streets. there were over 300 sister marches that took place simultaneously around the world in a show of solidarity.‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
the 2017 march was the spark for the mainstreaming of activism that has erupted over the past couple years, contributing to widespread participation in the #metoo, #timesup, and #neveragain movements. as such, those in attendance of women's marches this year are showing up in support of a wide variety of causes beyond just women's rights: climate action, solidarity with asylum-seekers and lgbtq rights are just some examples.‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
in canada, the cold snap hasn't stopped people from showing up in great numbers, supporting canadian-specific causes like the missing and murdered indigenous women and girls (mmiwg) movement.‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Ä¢‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Ä¢‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£

text:
silent lines
ucf art gallery january 10 ‚Äì february 14, 2019

as society addresses and attempts to rectify the rampant sexism plaguing creative as well as commercial communities, social media provides a platform for survivors to voice their experiences. movements like #metoo and #timesup create community for the abused, and unity for advocating change. but not all experiences fit neatly into a tweet, and not all pain can be conveyed with a hashtag.

acknowledging the complexity of abuse empowers the art of yvette cummings arendt.¬† processing her own experiences and translating them into art, she encourages viewers to bring their own experiences to her work. her thoughtful handling of the shared pain creates an exchange that blurs the line between artist and viewer.... for the rest is the article go to our website in our bio.

the recent articles of immigration of a criminal and a diplomat convicted of a sexual assault being bailed out by his government and fleeing. the most upsetting piece is pm trudeau inviting an international woman into canada to provide her protection. 
pm trudeau publicly admitted to his part of adding another woman to the #metoo campaign. he hasn‚Äôt serviced the tax paying canadian victims that are filling shelters in droves. there are victims still living with their abusers just waiting for space to open up. the oldest group of women of war are the caf victims of sadvr. they are still pows trying to live another day while protecting their children of rape. 
why isn‚Äôt pm trudeau looking after this group of victims. he isn‚Äôt prosecuting cafs pedophiles or perverts already identified by their victims. our cases aren‚Äôt being independently investigated. the military along side of our unjust system is only asking victims to step forward so that their evidence and medical files are placed under publication bans and gags orders while their rapist live freely.
we are canada‚Äôs oldest veterans. we spent our lives washing and ironing military uniforms and polishing boots all while crying from the chronic pain from the abuse we endured maybe hours before this.
our ptsd wasn‚Äôt brought on by one mere 6 mth tour but living as a pow on canadian soil 24/7, 365 days a year times the years under control.
where are our medals, parades and pensions. the war on military abused women is coming to a head.

in order for the healing process to begin we must speak our truth. thank you for your continued prayers for the victims and the victims families. here are some brave ladies that have decided to come forward and make public statements in regards to their experience. we continue to shine the light on these injustices. a source claims that casey treat, and the leaders of christian faith center (the treat family), are supportive and working towards bringing pastor moses back from his leave of absence, to work at the church again. you understand how alarming this is for the victims. predators don't work in public. they are sneaky, cunning and deceptive. i hope the parents at christian faith school will stand up against allowing this man back on the campus of the church. please go to¬†www.megachurchexploitation.com¬†to follow along on the latest news of the lawsuit. 
i know it's hard to wrap your mind around this for some people. trust me, i know the struggle between loyalty and doing what is right. what if this was your daughter or wife? this is not a representation of the church that god had intended. this is not an isolated event. churches everywhere are being exposed. this is spiritual warfare against the spirit of pride, greed, celebrity, and fame. we stand firm and know that god is fighting this battle. his fight, his victory. ---
blessings,
janet russell

text:
went to a march by myself: -for the times my best friends have been victims to assault/ rape.
-for the times guys have grabbed my ass and i pretended it never happened out of embarrassment.
-for the time i was assaulted at 16.
-for the many times my mom was assaulted because she didn‚Äôt know any english.
-for the time i was with someone physically abusive and let those memories be apart of the next relationship i had.
-for the time someone in my yoga class opened up about growing up being molested by her father and we cried together for her pain.
-for all the times girls are fearful in speaking up because things somehow end up being our fault.

i march for women. mothers. sisters. friends. trans. colored. blind. disabled. white. all. let‚Äôs ask the women around us today what they‚Äôve been through and listen. i‚Äôm so proud to live in a country that is so progressive and allows us to use our voices. usa politics change the world. american women change the world üíïüíüüíìüö∫üë∏üèªüë∏üèøüë∏üèΩüë∏üèæüë∏üèºüë©‚Äç‚ù§Ô∏è‚Äçüë©üëØ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüå∏

text:
people who eat darkness is a true story about a british girl who goes missing in tokyo. it's incredibly detailed, layered, complex, written in powerful prose. the storytelling ability of the author kept me fascinated from beginning to end. it's a compassionate study of lucies whole life, of her family, of other victims and the emotional aftermath of the tragedy. it takes a deep, hard look at the perpetrator and his childhood and life, trying to understand, without glorifying. the account of the investigation&search for lucie is riveting.the account of the court trials is mind boggling. all of this is intertwined with incredible insight and knowledge of japanese culture, the experience of being a foreigner in tokyo and the realities of working as a hostess. 
this story was especially chilling for me. i had a brush with similar hostess clubs, i met girls who worked as hostesses and i even tried working as one myself for a couple of days (and hated the experience) i was young, fascinated and fearless, i felt like nothing could possibly happen to me. but this is exactly what ended up being the demise of lucie. japan is a safe place, and it feels safe. walking alone at night as a woman is not a problem. men appear much more harmless, less intimidating, masculinity less aggressive and everyone seems bound by societal codes of conduct. to quote the author "the effect of this, for many foreigners, is to disable instincts of caution and suspicion that guide and protect them at home .conventional englishwomen would not have contemplated going to the apartment of a strange british man or working as a hostess in a london nightclub, in japan felt safe (to do that) japan was safe. and under its enchantment they made decisions that they would never have made anywhere else." it never occurred to me to think of it that way but reading thesewords, i realized it was exactly how i felt while briefly living in japan. i repeatedly put myself in very questionable situations, that i would never put myself in if it was my own country. it never crossed my mind to be weary of strangers, because this was japan, nothing would happen to me there. that, and being young lowered my guard down.

this story was especially chilling for me. i had a brush with similar hostess clubs, i met girls who worked as hostesses and i even tried working as one myself for a couple of days (and hated the experience) i was young, fascinated and fearless, i felt like nothing could possibly happen to me. but this is exactly what ended up being the demise of lucie. japan is a safe place, and it feels safe. walking alone at night as a woman is not a problem. men appear much more harmless, less intimidating, masculinity less aggressive and everyone seems bound by societal codes of conduct. to quote the author "the effect of this, for many foreigners, is to disable instincts of caution and suspicion that guide and protect them at home .conventional englishwomen would not have contemplated going to the apament of a strange british man or working as a hostess in a london nightclub, in japan felt safe (to do that) japan was safe. and under its enchantment they made decisions that they would never have made anywhere else." it never occurred to me to think of it that way but reading thesewords, i realized it was exactly how i felt while briefly living in japan. i repeatedly put myself in very questionable situations, that i would never put myself in if it was my own country. it never crossed my mind to be weary of strangers, because this was japan, nothing would happen to me there. that, and being young lowered my guard down.

text:
there‚Äôs something so refreshing about dogs. why are they often so happy? is it because they have far fewer responsibilities weighing on their shoulders as we do? is it due to their lower cognitive ability compared to adult humans? is it because they live ‚Äúa dog‚Äôs life‚Äù whereby everything they need is handed to them (quite literally) on a plate? partially, yes. but i think there is more to it. dogs possess an endearing optimism: that you will return home soon, that walkout time is just around the bend, that you will drop a crumb of food on the floor, that all people are kind and upfront. little things bring joy to dogs: fresh air, interaction, affection, food, water. it strikes me that we should mirror this appreciation for the small things. i have access to safe, clean water: great! i have food security: great! i have my freedom: great! i have friends, family, and the ability to connect with people: fantastic! not only do dogs bring us joy and companionship, they teach us that appreciating the simplicities of life and reassessing our values can go a long way in aiding our happiness and fulfilment. ~copingdiary
~
~
~

text:
oh. em. gee. i almost forgot what today is!!!
so on this day, annually, i celebrate as if it were my new years day as it marks the anniversary of the day i had my stroke-(this year marks 9 years). i woke up with a tingling in my face which turned into drooping and by the time i reached the hospital i couldn't feel the left side of my body. the doctors attributed this to a caustic amount of stress in my life that caused abnormally high blood pressure which forced a teeny clot through what should have been a benign hole in my heart. i spent 10 days in the hospital and several months in bed/pt. take it from me... no one is worth this much stress! 
loves, make a choice to be happy. this was my catalyst and my life is certainly tenfold happier now. üôÇ üíó
i am celebrating tonight. have a drink with me and be happy you are alive. cheers y'all!! üç∑üçªü•Çüç∫üçæ

text:
happier times. 
as we spend with our mom what are likely her last weeks of earthly life, i am overwhelmed with grief, frustration, confusion, adoration, denial, pride, hope, anger, fear, exhaustion. an endless list.
fluid feelings.
floods of emotion fill my days and dreams.  during conversations i look people in the eyes, but my mind meanders elsewhere. 
it turns out, the happiness in this photo was largely an illusion.
my mom and a few other people harbored a horrible secret. 
during the season the photographer snapped this photo, my mom survived an egregious attack. decades later that event would upend and reshape the lives of dozens more innocent people. the thought of that aggressive and selfish act pierces my heart every day. i accept it happened, but i will never get over it.
a silver lining looms though. i‚Äôm certain my mom‚Äôs headed to a better place and i find giddy joy in knowing her pain will end there.
i‚Äôve reflected on amazing moments together, like watching her round on the cops hand-signaling her to stop so they could ticket her for speeding. or the time she made a mud slide in the front yard for my brother and me. my mom and i danced like nobody was watching and we shared some magnificent meals and milestones.
it hurts deeply to watch my mom live with so much mental and physical pain, but i‚Äôve seen her strength in action, so i believe it‚Äôs a part of her soul even if it‚Äôs not evident in her body. 
she‚Äôs tougher than nails, having survived cancer and countless disappointments. the hardest obstacle she said she‚Äôd ever endured was the loss of a child.
during the 1970s, my mom birthed a stillborn baby. eleven months later, she visited her other two babies in the hospital at the same time (the oldest having suffered multiple seizures and the youngest a premature newborn).
when i was young these challenges didn‚Äôt phase me much. now, as a mother, i can‚Äôt imagine what that year must have felt like for her in real-time.
my mom‚Äôs scared about death but thrilled she will finally cradle her tiny baby again soon. that makes me smile.
i pray no matter how many days this warrior has left here comfort and peace overpower her pain.
#hospice #caregiver #pray #metoo

text:
ok @vivid_winner #pizzagate #pedogate #pedovore

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided repos about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
you have a voice.
it can be loud. it can be quiet. it can be sweet and dust your lips like powdered sugar. it can be harsh and cut your mouth as broken shards of glass fall out of your mouth. what do you want to say? taking your voice into your hands and making something. something that speaks for you. a visual representation of your truth. what colour are you? smearing your truth all over the landscape to reveal parts unknown and secrets unseen. give your voice its place to be heard. through your fingers or your toes. expose different parts of yourself to yourself. and share it. show it. scream it. whisper it. say it with colour smears and glue. pencil and feathers. light and dark. 
you have a voice. we want to see it. 
expose your exposure.
.
.
for more info and signing up please check our link in bio or email womensartshow15@gmail.com .
.
.

text:
this is my bitch face. my fed-up face. it's the wake of my first women's march, and snow or shine i am all there. because the wild woman in me has woken and is ready to do my part in raising up the feminine. 
alan watts wrote a book about the pulls of a man between spirit and nature. spirit is the masculine, and nature the feminine. that a man chooses between devoting his life wholly to god and spirit, or falling in submission to his feminine parts. this view is extreme and i do not adhere to it completely, but it brings up this interesting notion of a choice. he never questioned the natural instinct of a woman, but saw a choice for men to embrace their feminine parts in support of those they love, and learning to control aggression. i thank all men who embrace and/or support the feminine with an open mind. as always, some words to share:

may you let your feelings be tools of cognition.
instincts were first of nature, and the natural feminine in you holds the inner-truth of what you feel.
we are wild at our cores, but not in a way that is deemed vicious.
wild like the moon, feminine energy has us dance as a community around it.
as one with no sections of poorer worth or ability.
because the feminine is mysterious to the masculine is never a grounds to control the feminine.
if you say "no" to the future of the divine feminine, we have no obligation to adhere to that cry, for we have been criticized in saying "no" to the masculine control of our sex.
i see a world in which aggression may perish, and we all rise as one, embracing the feminine parts of us all.
where both sides to a story are heard and accepted.
where society holds true victims in a greater state of need than the falsely accused.
where those falsely accused digress from violence towards femininity, because we do hear you as long as you do not drag us down with anger.
where voices crying "metoo" are not criticized for latency, and are instead met with open arms of communal healing.
a world where we live not in fear.

ps: i don't like you very much, trump.

#womensmarch #naturewoman #wildwoman #earthwoman #metoo #divinefeminine

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've seen this going around for a few things lately.... trauma, assault and eating disorders mostly. and it always strikes me because i've experienced all three of those and with them, it is really f*ing hard to take responsibility. ‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
for me, the eating disorder was my way of coping with the assault, but i didn't realize this until many years later. and even still, it can be hard to grasp this concept. it seems so unfair right? like, 15 years of my life have been taken away because of someone else's horrible decisions. and what, he just walks away unbothered, not ever knowing i've suffered a day in my life from him? why is this my responsibility!? i get those thoughts. you‚Äôre not alone.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
even though people were there for me. so many people helped with therapy bills, hospital bills, driving me places, medicine costs, my uncontrollable crying and panic attacks, my extreme fears and anxiety. people supported and never gave up on me.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
but here's the thing.... no one can make me better. no one can do the work for me. as much as everyone so selflessly gave and did for me, it was (is) ultimately up to me to make a change. when i was able to begin taking responsibility for my own health and happiness, i began to see change. ‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
what happened to me will never be my fault, but healing and moving on and taking control of my self and life will always be my responsibility. a very hard concept for me... and many others i'm realizing. but we can do this. you can do this. i believe in you -- because i didn't believe in myself and here i am... proof that healing is possible.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
sending you love and hugs. be gentle with yourself. you‚Äôre not alone ‚ù§‚ú®üåà

text:
this weekend marks the third anniversary of the women‚Äôs march. it has been an amazing journey to watch the impact this organized march has had on communities and our country. this year, sadly, i have to sit this one out. however, that does not change my solidarity with the concept of what this march means to so many women, men, children, and communities. i‚Äôll be with you all in spirit. thank you for marching for me and others.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
we encourage you to always speak your mind and remind you that you have the absolute right to use your voice in protest! these marches tend to be peaceful, but i acknowledge that times are rough. topics such as immigration, child-parent separation at the border, and the #metoo movement are at the core for a lot of people this year. these things can become emotional.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
we want to help you out with some protesting tips. know your rights when you hit those streets today. check out our stories for tips from the @aclu_nationwide on your rights and actions as a protester. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
sending love, strength, and good vibes!

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
people try to help by giving me advice on how to get better often. i appreciate they mean well. however, i will never be better in the way they think as for someone like me it's so deep rooted it will always be part of me. i can learn to live with it, love myself and create a life of meaning. it will always be there though and have an effect on the decisions i make. healing for me is not getting better it is taming my demons so i'm in control of them. here is to my healing process as in 10-12 months time i go through therapy for the first time since i was 15 (31 now) based on sexual assault/childhood abuse (not growing up with domestic violence). to people trying to heal from #cptsd you can do this your not alone xx

text:
happy 89th birthday to the icon that is tippi hedren! tippi starred in my favourite hitchcock movie of all time 'the birds,' and two years ago, i had the privilege to interview the icon herself for image magazine (@image.ie)! it was a true 'pinch me' moment. as a film obsessive, it remains one of the best moments in my career to date. we spoke for over 30 minutes about her life, career, work as an animal rights activist and how much she loved ireland. it could even be said that she herself was a part of #metoo before it ever officially came into being - having endured and spoken out against repeated incidents of harassment during the making of her first film. she was humble, sweet and even invited me to visit her out in her shambala preserve - something i've yet to take her up on! have a read of our chat in the link in my bio if you wish üí´ .
.
.
.
.

text:
only a couple of weeks left in january. which means #humantraffickingawarenessmonth is almost over. but creating awareness does not need to end.

almost a year ago, i was looking for an internship to complete my college degree. i felt like i had applied to a hundred places. but i just wasn‚Äôt hearing anything back. i was getting discouraged.

then something almost comical happened. i was on @instagram and saw a post from @higgins.ben about a project called ‚Äúproject beautiful.‚Äù out of interest i clicked on the attached link and discovered @lovejusticeintl. something led me to an internship page and before i new what was happening, an application.

it wasn‚Äôt until after i‚Äôd already filled the application out and turned it in that i fully realized the scope of what i‚Äôd done. i just applied for an internship in nepal. üò±üò¨üò∂ what happened next, happened so fast. but it felt right. sure it was scary, but it was also exciting.

and so i found myself in nepal four months later. and i met these people in the above picture. and i got to walk alongside @lovejusticeintl in their mission to end human trafficking and the world‚Äôs greatest injustices.

it was a summer i will never forget. one that changed my life. more importantly, i got to see it change others lives, as beautiful girls were intercepted from becoming victims in modern day slavery. and it was seeing their lives change that really made it truly unforgettable.

if you want to be a part in changing others lives for good, in bringing justice back into the world, visit @lovejusticeintl page and click on their link in their bio.

because every life is beautiful and worth saving. and because your voice matters.

text:
the womens march 2019 is happening today!! i've got my signs ready to go although they come nowhere close to what i really need to say! i stand in unity with my fellow humans to march for equality, for women and men not to fear this world and to speak up and tell their truths! i march so little boys can show emotions freely and little girls can feel comfortable in their own skin! i  march for the missing indigenous women who can no longer rest peacefully!  i march for the women and men who receive daily abuse and pressure from their spouces who are supposed to love them and protect them not manipulate and harm!! unite with us today at 12pm outside of the lambton mall! show your support for the men and women in this world!

text:
in our community everyday, acts of violence and direct and indirect trauma happen daily if not hourly. many are fighting for change through policy, advocacy, and often support but are we addressing the trauma itself? are we ever processing the trauma? are we talking to our children about their experiences? are we using these moments as teachable moments? are we seeking counseling or therapy or are we perpetuating the cycle of violence by shoving down our experiences, passing blame and outright ignoring the pain we are in? i challenge all of us to unpack our trauma and teach another until we all are healed from our wounds and see our communities as safe havens! what are your ideas on changing how we address violence and trauma? üëë‚ú®üíïüíé

a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he‚Äôs the only straight man i‚Äôve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: lately i‚Äôve been getting a lot of questions like: ‚Äúhow can i be happy like you?‚Äù or ‚Äúhow can i be calm like you?‚Äù the thing is, as much joy that i was able to bring others in the past, i wasn‚Äôt able to give that to myself. i‚Äôve had my #metoo moments, a myriad of eating disorders, post partum came later for me when i stopped breastfeeding, serious of unfortunate events, drank and ate too much and i lived toooo fast. the only thing that has been healing and able to take me to the next level has been slowing down and tuning into what i really want and need. i stopped doing what i was ‚Äúsupposed to do‚Äù and started doing things every day that make me happy. these things include eating beautiful plant based foods, drinking tea, gathering with friends to play music, dance, practice yoga and spend a lot more time at home. so, my advice to be calmer and happier is to slow down even if you don‚Äôt have the luxury to be home all the time. you don‚Äôt have to rush, take a few minutes a day to breathe and find things you really love and do them every day. üì∏ @delaheart_ #mamattribe #slowdown #happiness #calm #goodvibesonly

text:
how i basically feel about the #gillettead:
üßë
"but on social media, one man called it 'a condescending ad from a company that relies on men buying their products.' another wrote that 'being a man is not a disease nor a pathology,' adding that 'it is grotesque to repeatedly ascribe collective guilt onto half of humanity known as men.'"
üßëüèª
like "how dare you market products to us and ask us to exhibit human decency?" üòÇ
üë®üèø
this sounds like #notallmen or what people of a certain hue say when they hear words like "white privilege" and "white supremacy." #alllivesmatter
üßëüèº
reminds me of when people boycotted nike and #colinkaepernick by cutting out the check mark/swoosh from their clothes.
üßëüèΩ
newsflash: nike and @gillette already have your money (but if you insist on being a fool, please dispose of your razors safely).
üßëüèæ
it saddens me deeply that people are more upset at being told to be morally decent than they are about #racism and #toxicmasculinity. it bothers me that this ad is seen as divisive -- and not by just a few people on the fringe.
üßëüèø
if you are offended when an ad or campaign challenges your privilege, ask yourself, "why?"
üë®
no one is saying that there is anything wrong with being a man -- unless you define masculinity as denigrating others. then it's problematic. you may not ascribe to toxic masculinity but you do benefit from patriarchy and #maleprivilege. and if you do not *actively* do your part to question your privilege, dismantle toxic masculinity and use your privilege to protect and promote the voices of the vulnerable other, you are part of the problem. you are complicit. silence is complicity. be offended.
üë®üèª
so this ad basically says what we've been saying since time immemorial and definitely since #metoo: #dobetter.
üë®üèº
we only ask that men do better because we know that they can. you have the potential to be better men.

text: tonight as sat in my rocking chair i found myself holding a few crystals in my hands and i was rubbing my hands cupped together in a motion that simulated "warming them up" and i became aware that, i didn't send any type of thought that "i want to rub my hands together with these crystals (which asked me to pick them up a few minutes before) in the direction i was rubbing". what was happening was completely on its own and i did not ask this to happen. so at a conscious level i asked myself "what does this mean", so i focused my attention into my hands and i could feel the warmth that was being generated but i knew that my hands are moving far too slow to be generating this warmth, so i focused on the warmth and when i did this, in an instance i had a vision which lasted a nano second but long enough to know that just happened, so i let go of trying to figure out what i just saw and it appeared again only this time it lasted longer, the vision was long enough to see what resembles a fracture in my physical vision, i saw the room in front of me, all that i was looking at split and as i remained in the lower portion of the split (there was 3 splits) the middle portion of the screen transformed itself from representing something that was my living room/ kitchen and became something different, it was like something was being injected into this potion of the video steam, like a movie, and the new "video stream" showed an entirely different reality, and each time the new vision updated itself the more i could see into that reality, what i saw first were hands rubbing themselves together with crystals in their hands, white hands, glowing a shade of "white" that was the color of love, it was warm and the light surrounded  the hands, pulsing, and the first thing i felt was wisdom beyond truth, ancient, aged, soft and when i looked down the hands towards the finger tips out from the finger tips projected light beams all moving forward, i saw it as individual projections of realities, and as the hands continued to move in a slow rotating warming motion the images continued to project from the hand through the finger tips. i will post more of this vision shortly :)

text:
manjima mohan on #metoo: some allegations are believable and some are not believable
#
manjima mohan, who is known for her tamil and malayalam films, has opened up about #metoo movement. the actress said that she has not faced any such instances in her career. manjima mohanmanjima mohan, who made her tamil debut in gautham menon's achcham yenbathu madamaiyada, went on to act in few handfuls of films like sathriyan and ipadai vellum. now, the actress is part of zam zam and devarattam.according to a tamil daily, the actress has opened up about the #metoo movement, which has called out many leading celebs of indian cinema.manjima was quoted as saying, "some allegations are believable and some allegations are not believable. but when you hear them, it makes your blood boil."the actress said that she has never faced any kind of sexual harassment in the film industry, and has never heard (first-person account) about such instances.in tamil, lyricist vairamuthu, director susi ganesan and actor radha ravi faced allegations of sexual harassment.manjima will next be seen in malayalam remake of hindi blockbuster queen. the film is titled zam zam.also read| chinmayi sripaada: kept distance from vairamuthu after he asked me to 'cooperate'also watch | benny dayal and chinmayi sripada on working with ar rahmanget real-time alerts‚Ä¶

text:
privileged:

straight, white, middle class male, privileged,
sat well fed & clothed, lounging in the house i own,
books & magazines are everywhere in my home,
to read is to learn but also to live a life not your own,
so, i feast on history, news & novels as if starved,
knowing the only hunger i‚Äôve ever felt in my life is to know more,
and i read with righteous anger at society‚Äôs many wrongs,
for every emancipation there‚Äôs segregation, too much degradation,
it‚Äôs clear every damn battle for equality has shed too much blood,
or so it seems, sat in my conservatory, rolex on my wrist,
i look at my wife with deep love & warm glowing pride,
not a possession or bauble but a strong, independent woman,
but it burns me to think of the prejudices she‚Äôs faced,
just for being a woman even in this day & age,
#metoo, #timesup, #blacklivesmatter shows how far still we have to go,
no ‚Äòwhites only‚Äô buses & bars anymore but racism lurks,
my pale, white skin spots red with anger when i think this,
i try looking for positives, focus on the good, try to be a better man,
then worry i‚Äôm mansplaining when i explain why this matters,
the fragile male ego assuming my words count or carry weight,
am i so arrogant that i think my thoughts will make a difference,
domestic violence, corruption, racism, sexism, ageism, just being a dick,
all cured by the strokes of my montblanc pen on smythson paper,
if i‚Äôm being honest the truth is i‚Äôm scared about what i am,
could it be i‚Äôm an ignorant bigot with too many silk ties, too many words?
that my cosseted upbringing makes it easy to hide in plain sight,
that if this was sixty years ago i‚Äôd be living a very different life,
an alcoholic, wife beating, whites only, arrogant suited prick,
concerned only with the fold of my pocket square or next cocktail,
this is a hypothetical argument that seems impossible to resolve,
so instead of bleating on i should just take a simple step,
believe that i‚Äôm inherently good, that it‚Äôs not a privileged illusion,
like quitting the booze, just take it one step & day at a time,
continue being a good son, husband, friend & colleague,
and if this was sixty years ago, know i‚Äôd still feel the same way.

text:
the auditorium was filled with overflowing interest and attention when the keynote speaker, professor salome martinez salazar, took over the stage and presented layers and details of her life experiences as a mathematician and a woman in her workspace, in a male-dominated field of study. ‚Äòenvironment and changing gender equations‚Äô, was the theme of the keynote address. the lack of women professionals in her department, minimum women representation in stem education, significant wage gap, the #metoo movement, were some of the topics of her discussion , with respect to the state of chile universities and the challenges faced by the country. she pointed towards a change in priorities; towards improved protocols for harassment/ abuse cases, and non-sexist education. 
bringing an end to the inaugural session, ms. shama mitra chenoy addressed the audience with a vote of thanks and an expression of gratitude. 
with a short break, session i: women and health progressed. ms. aparna jain felicitated and introduced the speakers for the session. 
dr. ramesh awasthi, co-convenor and managing trustee, m a s u m, the first speaker of the session, talked about factors affecting women‚Äôs health; systematic failures in the form of poverty, poor environmental hygiene; absence of women‚Äôs rights on their own bodies; and abortion rights.
dr. nupur kohli, advisor-health advisory services at ey, netherlands, shared her presentation with a discussion on who facts on women and health. the significance of women health, be it physical or mental, was greatly emphasized. 
professor rama v. baru, jnu university, pointed her concern towards anemia in women. some important areas defining women‚Äôs health such as reproductive health, increase in bio-medicalization; along with the minimization of women health to mere risks were brought to light. 
the platform given to various major topics on women health left an ever-lasting impression on the audience, allowing them to have a better and informed outlook. 
ms. aparna jain, concluded the session, with a vote of thanks.
name: WDC,Shivaji College
